ocus on Rama and Krishna, i.e. soul and mind. Soul is seen as a representat=
ive of god in us, because of some basic attributes of it. It is the higher =
self and has no agendas, no likes or dislikes.=C2=A0Once mind fancies a sep=
arate existence with some agendas/desires, soul supports the
 individualize=
d consciousness stemming from that fancy and sees it as its dharma. It lend=
s strength and support to EVERY aspect of this individualized consciousness=
 (e.g. mind, energy, intellect, learning ability, enjoyment, discipline etc=
). It supports them fully and yet has no desires/agendas/likes/dislikes of =
its own! It impassionately witnesses and records all of one's agendas and k=
armas so that Laws of Nature give proper fruits later on. It does all that =
despite full awareness that it is neither doing those karmas nor receiving =
the fruits. As mind and other aspects of the individualized consciousness e=
ntertain the notion that they are doing things and begetting the fruits, so=
ul supports them fully in this play. It sees that as its dharma and does it=
 impassionately.=C2=A0Now, does this sound exciting? Perhaps not to all. Th=
is functionality of an impassionate witness supporting the play, may not se=
em interesting enough to some.=C2=A0On the other hand, mind
 has likes, dis=
likes and agendas. It is constantly pursuing those agendas, getting things =
and achieving things. Movement of mind is what keeps the individualization =
going!!! Though soul is the support for everything else in the individualiz=
ed consciousness, soul is a witness doing its dharma impassionately. It is =
mind that keeps the individualization going and brings in agendas and passi=
on and even decides/affects every entity's dharma. That way, mind is really=
 the "boss" of the individualization. No wonder Krishna's life appeals more=
 to one who may be excited by this description!=C2=A0*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=
=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0Lo=
rd Krishna is obviously awe-inspiring, but let me put Rama's life in perspe=
ctive.=C2=A0Rama's life demonstrates how soul operates. At a young age, he =
received Brahma Jnana from Vasishtha and became realized. Yet, he did whate=
ver was his "dharma". He helped Vishwamitra. Soon after marriage, he was gi=
ven kingdom. At the last moment, his father
 banished him to forest at the =
behest of his step-mother and his step-brother was given the throne. He had=
 no complaints. Though his father, step-mother and step-brother felt guilty=
 to various degrees, he himself supported and consoled all three and follow=
ed his dharma impassionately. Though he knew leaving Sita in the forest wit=
h Lakshmana and going after the golden deer would cause problems, he did it=
