arched for her and fought the battle. He never faulted Sita for forcing him=
 to leave her or faulted Lakshmana for leaving her later. He accepted every=
 life situation with no complaints and did the best possible action then. E=
ven as he killed Ravana, he did so without hatred or anger, but as his impa=
ssionate dharma. Even as Ravana was dying, he went to him and respectfully =
learned some subjects that were going to disappear with Ravana!=C2=A0Rama i=
s a perfect example of a liberated man
 with no desires or agendas who impa=
ssionately discharges one's dharma arising from the momentum of karmas befo=
re liberation. THAT is basically what soul does!=C2=A0*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=
